[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/data-stream] In connection-oriented communication, a **data stream** is the transmission of a sequence of digitally encoded signals to convey information.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/data-stream] Typically, the transmitted symbols are grouped into a series of packets.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/data-stream] Most data transmitted over the Internet is transmitted as a data stream.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/data-stream] Using a mobile phone to have a conversation transmits the sound as a data stream.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/data-stream] 2. $\Delta$ is a sequence of positive real time intervals.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/data-stream] Data Stream contains different sets of data, that depend on the chosen data format.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/data-stream] A **data point** is a tag that collects information about a certain action, performed by a user on a website.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/data-stream] Data points exists in two types, the values of which are used to create appropriate audiences.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/data-stream] Information gathered out of websites are based on user behavior.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/data-stream] Data providers deliver both personal or non-personal information.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/fan-out-software] In software construction, the fan-out of a class or method is the number of other classes used by that class or the number of other methods called by that method.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/fan-out-software] Additionally, fan-out has impact on the quality of a software.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] In computer science, **message passing** is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message to a process (which may be an actor or object) and relies on that process and its supporting infrastructure to then select and run some appropriate code.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Message passing differs from conventional programming where a process, subroutine, or function is directly invoked by name.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Message passing is key to some models of concurrency and object-oriented programming.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Message passing is ubiquitous in modern computer software.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] It is used as a way for the objects that make up a program to work with each other and as a means for objects and systems running on different computers (e.g., the Internet) to interact.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Message passing may be implemented by various mechanisms, including channels.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Message passing is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] In contrast to the traditional technique of calling a program by name, message passing uses an object model to distinguish the general function from the specific implementations.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message and relies on the object to select and execute the appropriate code.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] The justifications for using an intermediate layer essentially falls into two categories: encapsulation and distribution.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Message passing is a core technique used for communication between processes, threads, objects, or nodes in both concurrent and distributed systems.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] It enables software components to exchange information without sharing memory, often using communication channels, buffers, or middleware to transport messages between senders and receivers.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] In some models, message passing can be implemented synchronously, where the sender waits for a reply, or asynchronously, where messages are queued for later processing.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Encapsulation is the idea that software objects should be able to invoke services on other objects without knowing or caring about how those services are implemented.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Encapsulation can reduce the amount of coding logic and make systems more maintainable.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] E.g., rather than having IF-THEN statements that determine which subroutine or function to call, a developer can just send a message to the object and the object will select the appropriate code based on its type.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] One of the first examples of how this can be used was in the domain of computer graphics.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] There are various complexities involved in manipulating graphic objects.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] For example, simply using the right formula to compute the area of an enclosed shape will vary depending on if the shape is a triangle, rectangle, ellipse, or circle.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] In traditional computer programming, this would result in long IF-THEN statements testing what sort of object the shape was and calling the appropriate code.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] The object-oriented way to handle this is to define a class called `Shape` with subclasses such as `Rectangle` and `Ellipse` (which, in turn, have subclasses `Square` and `Circle`) and then to simply send a message to any `Shape` asking it to compute its area.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Each `Shape` object will then invoke the subclass's method with the formula appropriate for that kind of object.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Distributed message passing provides developers with a layer of the architecture that provides common services to build systems made up of sub-systems that run on disparate computers in different locations and at different times.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Synchronous message passing occurs between objects that are running at the same time.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] It is used by object-oriented programming languages such as Java and Smalltalk.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Synchronous messaging is analogous to a synchronous function call; just as the function caller waits until the function completes, the sending process waits until the receiving process accepts the message.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] This can make synchronous communication unworkable for some applications.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] For example, large, distributed systems may not perform well enough to be usable.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Such large, distributed systems may need to operate while some of their subsystems are down for maintenance, etc.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Imagine a busy business office having 100 desktop computers that send emails to each other using synchronous message passing exclusively.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] One worker turning off their computer can cause the other 99 computers to freeze until the worker turns their computer back on to process a single email.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Message passing systems can be broadly categorized based on how send and receive operations interact with executing processes.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] In **synchronous** message passing, the sending process may block until the receiver has accepted the message, ensuring tight coordination.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] In **asynchronous** models, the sender continues execution after sending a message, and messages are typically stored in a queue or buffer until the receiving process retrieves them.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] With asynchronous message passing the receiving object can be down or busy when the requesting object sends the message.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Continuing the function call analogy, it is like a function call that returns immediately, without waiting for the called function to complete.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Messages are sent to a queue where they are stored until the receiving process requests them.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] The receiving process processes its messages and sends results to a queue for pickup by the original process (or some designated next process).
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Asynchronous messaging requires additional capabilities for storing and retransmitting data for systems that may not run concurrently, and are generally handled by an intermediary level of software (often called middleware); a common type being Message-oriented middleware (MOM).
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] The buffer required in asynchronous communication can cause problems when it is full.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] A decision has to be made whether to block the sender or whether to discard future messages.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] If messages are dropped, communication is no longer reliable.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Synchronous communication can be built on top of asynchronous communication by using a Synchronizer.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] For example, the α-Synchronizer works by ensuring that the sender always waits for an acknowledgement message from the receiver.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] The sender only sends the next message after the acknowledgement has been received.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] On the other hand, asynchronous communication can also be built on top of synchronous communication.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] For example, modern microkernels generally only provide a synchronous messaging primitive and asynchronous messaging can be implemented on top by using helper threads.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Message-passing systems use either distributed or local objects.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] With distributed objects the sender and receiver may be on different computers, running different operating systems, using different programming languages, etc.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] In this case the bus layer takes care of details about converting data from one system to another, sending and receiving data across the network, etc.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] The Remote Procedure Call (RPC) protocol in Unix was an early example of this.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] With this type of message passing it is not a requirement that sender nor receiver use object-oriented programming.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Procedural language systems can be wrapped and treated as large grained objects capable of sending and receiving messages.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Examples of systems that support distributed objects are: Emerald, ONC RPC, CORBA, Java RMI, DCOM, SOAP, .NET Remoting, CTOS, QNX Neutrino RTOS, OpenBinder and D-Bus.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Distributed object systems have been called "shared nothing" systems because the message passing abstraction hides underlying state changes that may be used in the implementation of sending messages.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Distributed, or asynchronous, message-passing has additional overhead compared to calling a procedure.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] In message-passing, arguments must be copied to the new message.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Some arguments can contain megabytes of data, all of which must be copied and transmitted to the receiving object.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Traditional procedure calls differ from message-passing in terms of memory usage, transfer time and locality.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Arguments are passed to the receiver typically by general-purpose registers requiring no additional storage nor transfer time, or in a parameter list containing the arguments' addresses (a few bits).
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Address-passing is not possible for distributed systems since the systems use separate address spaces.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Web browsers and web servers are examples of processes that communicate by message-passing.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] A URL is an example of referencing a resource without exposing process internals.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] A subroutine call or method invocation will not exit until the invoked computation has terminated.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Asynchronous message-passing, by contrast, can result in a response arriving a significant time after the request message was sent.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] A message-handler will, in general, process messages from more than one sender.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] This means its state can change for reasons unrelated to the behavior of a single sender or client process.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] This is in contrast to the typical behavior of an object upon which methods are being invoked: the latter is expected to remain in the same state between method invocations.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] In other words, the message-handler behaves analogously to a volatile object.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] The prominent mathematical models of message passing are the Actor model and Pi calculus.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] In mathematical terms a message is the single means to pass control to an object.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] If the object responds to the message, it has a method for that message.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] Alan Kay has argued that message passing is more important than objects in OOP, and that objects themselves are often over-emphasized.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/message-passing] The live distributed objects programming model builds upon this observation; it uses the concept of a distributed data flow to characterize the behavior of a complex distributed system in terms of message patterns, using high-level, functional-style specifications.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] In software architecture, the **publish–subscribe pattern** (**pub/sub**) is a messaging pattern in which message senders, called **publishers**, categorize messages into classes (or *topics*), and send them without needing to know which components will receive them.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Message recipients, called **subscribers**, express interest in one or more classes and only receive messages in those classes, without needing to know the identity of the publishers.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern decouples the components that produce messages from those that consume them, and supports asynchronous, many-to-many communication.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] The publish–subscribe model is commonly contrasted with message queue-based and point-to-point messaging models, where producers send messages directly to consumers.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publish–subscribe is a sibling of the message queue paradigm, and is typically a component of larger message-oriented middleware systems.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many modern messaging frameworks and protocols, such as the Java Message Service (JMS), Apache Kafka, and MQTT, support both the pub/sub and queue-based models.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern provides greater network scalability and supports more dynamic topologies, but can make it harder to modify the publisher’s logic or the structure of the published data.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Compared to synchronous patterns like RPC and point-to-point messaging, publish–subscribe provides the highest level of decoupling among architectural components.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, it can also lead to semantic or format coupling between publishers and subscribers, which may cause systems to become entangled or brittle over time.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] In publish–subscribe systems, subscribers typically receive only a subset of messages.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] In most pub/sub systems, publishers and subscribers communicate through a central intermediary such as a message broker or event bus.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] The broker receives messages from publishers and forwards them to the appropriate subscribers, optionally performing store and forward, priority queuing, or other routing logic.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Some pub/sub systems use **brokerless** architectures, in which publishers and subscribers discover each other and exchange messages directly.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, the Data Distribution Service (DDS) middleware uses IP multicast and metadata sharing to establish communication paths.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokerless systems require construction of overlay networks, often using Small-World topologies to enable efficient routing.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] It was shown by Jon Kleinberg that efficient decentralized routing requires Navigable Small-World topologies, which are employed in federated or peer-to-peer pub/sub systems.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Locality-aware pub/sub networks use low-latency links to reduce message propagation time.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] One of the earliest publicly described pub/sub systems was the "news" subsystem of the Isis Toolkit, presented at the 1987 ACM Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP '87).
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] As distributed systems became more common, the publish–subscribe model evolved to emphasize asynchronous messaging and broker-mediated communication, setting it apart from the more tightly coupled observer pattern.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publishers are loosely coupled to subscribers, and need not even know of their existence.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] With the topic being the focus, publishers and subscribers are allowed to remain ignorant of system topology.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Each can continue to operate as per normal independently of the other.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] In the traditional tightly coupled client–server paradigm, the client cannot post messages to the server while the server process is not running, nor can the server receive messages unless the client is running.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many pub/sub systems decouple not only the locations of the publishers and subscribers but also decouple them temporally.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] A common strategy used by middleware analysts with such pub/sub systems is to take down a publisher to allow the subscriber to work through the backlog (a form of bandwidth throttling).
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Pub/sub provides the opportunity for better scalability than traditional client-server, through parallel operation, message caching, tree-based or network-based routing, etc.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Outside of the enterprise environment, on the other hand, the pub/sub paradigm has proven its scalability to volumes far beyond those of a single data center, providing Internet-wide distributed messaging through web syndication protocols such as RSS and Atom.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] These syndication protocols accept higher latency and lack of delivery guarantees in exchange for the ability for even a low-end web server to syndicate messages to (potentially) millions of separate subscriber nodes.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Redundant subscribers in a pub/sub system can help assure message delivery with minimal additional complexity.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, a factory may utilize a pub/sub system where equipment can publish problems or failures to a subscriber that displays and logs those problems.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] If the logger fails (crashes), equipment problem publishers won't necessarily receive notice of the logger failure, and error messages will not be displayed or recorded by any equipment on the pub/sub system.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a client/server system, when an error logger fails, the system will receive an indication of the error logger (server) failure.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, the client/server system will have to deal with that failure by having redundant logging servers online, or by dynamically spawning fallback logging servers.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] This adds complexity to the client and server designs, as well as to the client/server architecture as a whole.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a pub/sub system, redundant logging subscribers that are exact duplicates of the existing logger can be added to the system to increase logging reliability without any impact to any other equipment on the system.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] The feature of assured error message logging can also be added incrementally, subsequent to implementing the basic functionality of equipment problem message logging.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] The most serious problems with pub/sub systems are a side-effect of their main advantage: the decoupling of publisher from subscriber.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] A pub/sub system must be designed carefully to be able to provide stronger system properties that a particular application might require, such as assured delivery.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] The pub/sub pattern scales well for small networks with a small number of publisher and subscriber nodes and low message volume.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, as the number of nodes and messages grows, the likelihood of instabilities increases, limiting the maximum scalability of a pub/sub network.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] For pub/sub systems that use brokers (servers), the argument for a broker to send messages to a subscriber is in-band, and can be subject to security problems.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers might be fooled into sending notifications to the wrong client, amplifying denial of service requests against the client.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers themselves could be overloaded as they allocate resources to track created subscriptions.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Even with systems that do not rely on brokers, a subscriber might be able to receive data that it is not authorized to receive.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] An unauthorized publisher may be able to introduce incorrect or damaging messages into the pub/sub system.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] This is especially true with systems that broadcast or multicast their messages.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS)) can prevent unauthorized access, but cannot prevent damaging messages from being introduced by authorized publishers.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/publish-subscribe-pattern] Architectures other than pub/sub, such as client/server systems, are also vulnerable to authorized message senders that behave maliciously.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Queueing theory has its origins in research by Agner Krarup Erlang, who created models to describe the system of incoming calls at the Copenhagen Telephone Exchange Company.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] These ideas were seminal to the field of teletraffic engineering and have since seen applications in telecommunications, traffic engineering, computing, project management, and particularly industrial engineering, where they are applied in the design of factories, shops, offices, and hospitals.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Queueing theory is one of the major areas of study in the discipline of management science.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Through management science, businesses are able to solve a variety of problems using different scientific and mathematical approaches.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Queueing analysis is the probabilistic analysis of waiting lines, and thus the results, also referred to as the operating characteristics, are probabilistic rather than deterministic.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The overall goal of queueing analysis is to compute these characteristics for the current system and then test several alternatives that could lead to improvement.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Computing the operating characteristics for the current system and comparing the values to the characteristics of the alternative systems allows managers to see the pros and cons of each potential option.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] These systems help in the final decision making process by showing ways to increase savings, reduce waiting time, improve efficiency, etc.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The main queueing models that can be used are the single-server waiting line system and the multiple-server waiting line system, which are discussed further below.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] These models can be further differentiated depending on whether service times are constant or undefined, the queue length is finite, the calling population is finite, etc.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] A *queue* or *queueing node* can be thought of as nearly a black box.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] *Jobs* (also called *customers* or *requests*, depending on the field) arrive to the queue, possibly wait some time, take some time being processed, and then depart from the queue.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] However, the queueing node is not quite a pure black box since some information is needed about the inside of the queueing node.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The queue has one or more *servers* which can each be paired with an arriving job.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] When the job is completed and departs, that server will again be free to be paired with another arriving job.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] An analogy often used is that of the cashier at a supermarket.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Customers arrive, are processed by the cashier, and depart.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Each cashier processes one customer at a time, and hence this is a queueing node with only one server.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] A setting where a customer will leave immediately if the cashier is busy when the customer arrives, is referred to as a queue with no *buffer* (or no *waiting area*).
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] A setting with a waiting zone for up to *n* customers is called a queue with a buffer of size *n*.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The behaviour of a single queue (also called a *queueing node*) can be described by a birth–death process, which describes the arrivals and departures from the queue, along with the number of jobs currently in the system.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] If *k* denotes the number of jobs in the system (either being serviced or waiting if the queue has a buffer of waiting jobs), then an arrival increases *k* by 1 and a departure decreases *k* by 1.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The system transitions between values of *k* by *births* and *deaths*, which occur at the arrival rates $\lambda _{i}$ and the departure rates $\mu _{i}$ for each job i .
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] For a queue, these rates are generally considered not to vary with the number of jobs in the queue, so a single average rate of arrivals/departures per unit time is assumed.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The steady state equations for the birth-and-death process, known as the balance equations, are as follows.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Here $P_{n}$ denotes the steady state probability to be in state *n*.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] which, together with the equation for $P_{n}$ $(n\geq 1)$ , fully describes the required steady state probabilities.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Single queueing nodes are usually described using Kendall's notation in the form A/S/*c* where *A* describes the distribution of durations between each arrival to the queue, *S* the distribution of service times for jobs, and *c* the number of servers at the node.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] For an example of the notation, the M/M/1 queue is a simple model where a single server serves jobs that arrive according to a Poisson process (where inter-arrival durations are exponentially distributed) and have exponentially distributed service times (the M denotes a Markov process).
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] In an M/G/1 queue, the G stands for *general* and indicates an arbitrary probability distribution for service times.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Further, let $E_{n}$ represent the number of times the system enters state *n*, and $L_{n}$ represent the number of times the system leaves state *n*.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] That is, the number of times the system leaves a state differs by at most 1 from the number of times it enters that state, since it will either return into that state at some time in the future ( $E_{n}=L_{n}$ ) or not ( $\left\vert E_{n}-L_{n}\right\vert =1$ ).
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] When the system arrives at a steady state, the arrival rate should be equal to the departure rate.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] A common basic queueing system is attributed to Erlang and is a modification of Little's Law.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Assuming an exponential distribution for the rates, the waiting time *W* can be defined as the proportion of arrivals that are served.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The two-stage one-box model is common in epidemiology.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] In 1909, Agner Krarup Erlang, a Danish engineer who worked for the Copenhagen Telephone Exchange, published the first paper on what would now be called queueing theory.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] He modeled the number of telephone calls arriving at an exchange by a Poisson process and solved the M/D/1 queue in 1917 and M/D/*k* queueing model in 1920.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] If the node has more jobs than servers, then jobs will queue and wait for service.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The M/G/1 queue was solved by Felix Pollaczek in 1930, a solution later recast in probabilistic terms by Aleksandr Khinchin and now known as the Pollaczek–Khinchine formula.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] After the 1940s, queueing theory became an area of research interest to mathematicians.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] In 1953, David George Kendall solved the GI/M/*k* queue and introduced the modern notation for queues, now known as Kendall's notation.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] In 1957, Pollaczek studied the GI/G/1 using an integral equation.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] John Kingman gave a formula for the mean waiting time in a G/G/1 queue, now known as Kingman's formula.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Leonard Kleinrock worked on the application of queueing theory to message switching in the early 1960s and packet switching in the early 1970s.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] His initial contribution to this field was his doctoral thesis at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in 1962, published in book form in 1964.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] His theoretical work published in the early 1970s underpinned the use of packet switching in the ARPANET, a forerunner to the Internet.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The matrix geometric method and matrix analytic methods have allowed queues with phase-type distributed inter-arrival and service time distributions to be considered.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Systems with coupled orbits are an important part in queueing theory in the application to wireless networks and signal processing.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Modern day application of queueing theory concerns among other things product development where (material) products have a spatiotemporal existence, in the sense that products have a certain volume and a certain duration.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Problems such as performance metrics for the M/G/*k* queue remain an open problem.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] this principle states that customers are served one at a time and that the customer that has been waiting the longest is served first.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Service capacity is shared equally between customers.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] (ROS), this discipline states that the next job served is selected at random from the jobs waiting in the queue.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Customers with high priority are served first.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] (where a job in service can be interrupted by a higher-priority job).
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The next job to be served is the one with the smallest size.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The next job to be served is the one with the smallest original size.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The next job to serve is the one with the smallest remaining processing requirement.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Server failures occur according to a stochastic (random) process (usually Poisson) and are followed by setup periods during which the server is unavailable.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The interrupted customer remains in the service area until server is fixed.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Arriving customers not served (either due to the queue having no buffer, or due to balking or reneging by the customer) are also known as *dropouts*.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The average rate of dropouts is a significant parameter describing a queue.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Queue networks are systems in which multiple queues are connected by *customer routing*.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] When a customer is serviced at one node, it can join another node and queue for service, or leave the network.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] For networks of *m* nodes, the state of the system can be described by an *m*–dimensional vector (*x*1, *x*2, ..., *x**m*) where *x**i* represents the number of customers at each node.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The simplest non-trivial networks of queues are called tandem queues.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The first significant results in this area were Jackson networks, for which an efficient product-form stationary distribution exists and the mean value analysis (which allows average metrics such as throughput and sojourn times) can be computed.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] If the total number of customers in the network remains constant, the network is called a *closed network* and has been shown to also have a product–form stationary distribution by the Gordon–Newell theorem.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] This result was extended to the BCMP network, where a network with very general service time, regimes, and customer routing is shown to also exhibit a product–form stationary distribution.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The normalizing constant can be calculated with the Buzen's algorithm, proposed in 1973.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Networks of customers have also been investigated, such as Kelly networks, where customers of different classes experience different priority levels at different service nodes.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Another type of network are G-networks, first proposed by Erol Gelenbe in 1993: these networks do not assume exponential time distributions like the classic Jackson network.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] In discrete-time networks where there is a constraint on which service nodes can be active at any time, the max-weight scheduling algorithm chooses a service policy to give optimal throughput in the case that each job visits only a single-person service node.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] In the more general case where jobs can visit more than one node, backpressure routing gives optimal throughput.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] A network scheduler must choose a queueing algorithm, which affects the characteristics of the larger network.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Mean-field models consider the limiting behaviour of the empirical measure (proportion of queues in different states) as the number of queues *m* approaches infinity.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The impact of other queues on any given queue in the network is approximated by a differential equation.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The deterministic model converges to the same stationary distribution as the original model.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] In a system with high occupancy rates (utilisation near 1), a heavy traffic approximation can be used to approximate the queueing length process by a reflected Brownian motion, Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process, or more general diffusion process.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The number of dimensions of the Brownian process is equal to the number of queueing nodes, with the diffusion restricted to the non-negative orthant.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Fluid models are continuous deterministic analogs of queueing networks obtained by taking the limit when the process is scaled in time and space, allowing heterogeneous objects.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] This scaled trajectory converges to a deterministic equation which allows the stability of the system to be proven.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] It is known that a queueing network can be stable but have an unstable fluid limit.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Queueing theory finds widespread application in computer science and information technology.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] In networking, for instance, queues are integral to routers and switches, where packets queue up for transmission.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] By applying queueing theory principles, designers can optimize these systems, ensuring responsive performance and efficient resource utilization.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Beyond the technological realm, queueing theory is relevant to everyday experiences.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Whether waiting in line at a supermarket or for public transportation, understanding the principles of queueing theory provides valuable insights into optimizing these systems for enhanced user satisfaction.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] At some point, everyone will be involved in an aspect of queuing.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] What some may view to be an inconvenience could possibly be the most effective method.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Queueing theory, a discipline rooted in applied mathematics and computer science, is a field dedicated to the study and analysis of queues, or waiting lines, and their implications across a diverse range of applications.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] This theoretical framework has proven instrumental in understanding and optimizing the efficiency of systems characterized by the presence of queues.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The study of queues is essential in contexts such as traffic systems, computer networks, telecommunications, and service operations.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] Queueing theory delves into various foundational concepts, with the arrival process and service process being central.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The arrival process describes the manner in which entities join the queue over time, often modeled using stochastic processes like Poisson processes.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] The efficiency of queueing systems is gauged through key performance metrics.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] These include the average queue length, average wait time, and system throughput.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/queueing-theory] These metrics provide insights into the system's functionality, guiding decisions aimed at enhancing performance and reducing wait times.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The **aggregate throughput** is the sum of the data rates that are delivered over all channels in a network.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Throughput represents digital bandwidth consumption.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The throughput of a communication system may be affected by various factors, including the limitations of the underlying physical medium, available processing power of the system components, end-user behavior, etc.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] When taking various protocol overheads into account, the useful rate of the data transfer can be significantly lower than the maximum achievable throughput; the useful part is usually referred to as goodput.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Users of telecommunications devices, systems designers, and researchers into communication theory are often interested in knowing the expected performance of a system.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] From a user perspective, this is often phrased as either "which device will get my data there most effectively for my needs?", or "which device will deliver the most data per unit cost?".
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Systems designers often select the most effective architecture or design constraints for a system, which drive its final performance.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] In most cases, the benchmark of what a system is capable of, or its *maximum performance* is what the user or designer is interested in.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The term *maximum throughput* is frequently used when discussing end-user maximum throughput tests.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Maximum throughput is essentially synonymous with digital bandwidth capacity.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Four different values are relevant in the context of maximum throughput are used in comparing the *upper limit* conceptual performance of multiple systems.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] They are *maximum theoretical throughput*, *maximum achievable throughput*, *peak measured throughput*, and *maximum sustained throughput*.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] These values represent different qualities, and care must be taken that the same definitions are used when comparing different *maximum throughput* values.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Each bit must carry the same amount of information if throughput values are to be compared.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Data compression can significantly alter throughput calculations, including generating values exceeding 100% in some cases.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] If the communication is mediated by several links in series with different bit rates, the maximum throughput of the overall link is lower than or equal to the lowest bit rate.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The lowest value link in the series is referred to as the bottleneck.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Maximum theoretical throughput is closely related to the channel capacity of the system, and is the maximum possible quantity of data that can be transmitted under ideal circumstances.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] In some cases, this number is reported as equal to the channel capacity, though this can be deceptive, as only non-packetized systems technologies can achieve this.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Maximum theoretical throughput is more accurately reported taking into account format and specification overhead with best-case assumptions.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The **asymptotic throughput** (less formal **asymptotic bandwidth**) for a packet-mode communication network is the value of the maximum throughput function, when the incoming network load approaches infinity, either due to a message size, or the number of data sources.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] As with other bit rates and data bandwidths, the asymptotic throughput is measured in bits per second (bit/s) or (rarely) bytes per second (B/s), where 1 B/s is 8 bit/s.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Decimal prefixes are used, meaning that 1 Mbit/s is 1000000 bit/s.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Asymptotic throughput is usually estimated by sending or simulating a very large message (sequence of data packets) through the network, using a greedy source and no flow control mechanism (i.e., UDP rather than TCP), and measuring the volume of data received at the destination node.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Traffic load between other sources may reduce this maximum network path throughput.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Alternatively, a large number of sources and sinks may be modeled, with or without flow control, and the aggregate maximum network throughput measured (the sum of traffic reaching its destinations).
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] A well-known application of asymptotic throughput is in modeling point-to-point communication where message latency $T(N)$ is modeled as a function of message length N as $T(N)=(M+N)/A$ where A is the asymptotic bandwidth and M is the half-peak length.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] As well as its use in general network modeling, asymptotic throughput is used in modeling performance on massively parallel computer systems, where system operation is highly dependent on communication overhead, as well as processor performance.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] In these applications, asymptotic throughput is used modeling which includes the number of processors, so that both the latency and the asymptotic throughput are functions of the number of processors.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Where asymptotic throughput is a theoretical or calculated capacity, *peak measured throughput* is throughput measured on a real implemented system, or on a simulated system.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The value is the throughput measured over a short period of time; mathematically, this is the limit taken with respect to throughput as time approaches zero.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] This term is synonymous with *instantaneous throughput*.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] This number is useful for systems that rely on burst data transmission; however, for systems with a high duty cycle, this is less likely to be a useful measure of system performance.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Maximum sustained throughput is the throughput averaged or integrated over a long time.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] For networks under constant load, this is likely to be the most accurate indicator of system performance.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The maximum throughput is defined as the asymptotic throughput when the load is large.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] In packet-switched networks while packet loss is not occurring, the load and the throughput always are equal.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The maximum throughput may be defined as the minimum load in bit/s that causes packet loss or causes the latency to become unstable and increase towards infinity.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Throughput is sometimes normalized and measured in percentage, but normalization may cause confusion regarding what the percentage is related to.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] *Channel utilization*, *channel efficiency* and *packet drop rate* in percentage are less ambiguous terms.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The channel efficiency, also known as bandwidth utilization efficiency, is the percentage of the net bit rate (in bit/s) of a digital communication channel that goes to the achieved throughput.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] For example, if the throughput is 70 Mbit/s over a 100 Mbit/s Ethernet connection, the channel efficiency is 70%.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Channel utilization includes both the data bits and the transmission overhead in the channel.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The transmission overhead consists of preamble sequences, frame headers and acknowledgment packets.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] In a simplistic approach, channel efficiency can be equal to channel utilization assuming that acknowledge packets are zero-length and that the communications provider will not see any bandwidth relative to retransmissions or headers.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Therefore, certain texts mark a difference between channel utilization and protocol efficiency.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] For example, the maximum frame size in Ethernet is 1526 bytes: up to 1500 bytes for the payload, eight bytes for the preamble, 14 bytes for the header, and 4 bytes for the trailer.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] An additional minimum interframe gap corresponding to 12 bytes is inserted after each frame.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] This corresponds to a maximum channel utilization of 1526 / (1526 + 12) × 100% = 99.22%, or a maximum channel use of 99.22 Mbit/s inclusive of Ethernet datalink layer protocol overhead over a 100 Mbit/s Ethernet connection.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The maximum throughput or channel efficiency is then 1500 / (1526 + 12) = 97.5%, exclusive of the Ethernet protocol overhead.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The throughput of a communication system will be limited by a number of factors.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The maximum achievable throughput (the channel capacity) is affected by the bandwidth in hertz and signal-to-noise ratio of the analog physical medium.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Limited current drive capability in communications equipment can limit the effective signal-to-noise ratio for high capacitance links.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Despite the conceptual simplicity of digital information, all electrical signals traveling over wires are analog.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The analog limitations of wires or wireless systems inevitably provide an upper bound on the amount of information that can be sent.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The dominant equation here is the Shannon–Hartley theorem, and analog limitations of this type can be understood as factors that affect either the analog bandwidth of a signal or as factors that affect the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The bandwidth of twisted pair cabling used by Ethernet is limited to approximately 1 GHz, and PCB traces are limited by a similar amount.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Digital systems refer to the *knee frequency*, the amount of time for the digital voltage to rise from 10% of a nominal digital 0 to a nominal digital 1 or vice versa.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Large data loads that require processing impose data processing requirements on hardware.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] For example, a gateway router must examine and perform routing table lookups on billions of packets per second.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] CSMA/CD and CSMA/CA backoff waiting time and frame retransmissions after detected collisions slows transmissions.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] This may occur in Ethernet bus networks and hub networks, as well as in wireless networks.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Flow control, for example, in the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) protocol, affects the throughput if the bandwidth-delay product is larger than the TCP window.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] In that case, the sending computer must wait for acknowledgement of the data packets before it can send more packets.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] TCP congestion avoidance controls the data rate.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] A so-called *slow start* occurs in the beginning of a file transfer, and after packet drops caused by router congestion or bit errors in, for example, wireless links.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Ensuring that multiple users can harmoniously share a single communications link requires some kind of equitable sharing of the link.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] If a communication link offering data rate *R* is shared by *N* active users, ideally, every user can typically achieve a throughput of approximately *R/N*.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Network schedulers in routers and switches ultimately determine how bandwidth is shared.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] If fair queuing is not provided, users that send large packets will get higher bandwidth.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Some users may be prioritized in a weighted fair queuing (WFQ) algorithm if differentiated or guaranteed quality of service (QoS) is provided.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] In some communications systems, such as satellite networks, only a finite number of channels may be available to a given user at a given time.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Channels are assigned either through preassignment or through Demand Assigned Multiple Access (DAMA).
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] In these cases, throughput is quantized per channel, and unused capacity on partially utilized channels is lost.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The maximum throughput is often an unreliable measurement of effective bandwidth, for example the file transmission data rate in bits per seconds.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The achieved throughput is often lower than the maximum throughput.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Protocol overhead affects the effective bandwidth.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] In schemes that include forward error correction codes, the redundant error code is normally excluded from the throughput.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] An example in modem communication, where the throughput is typically measured in the interface between the Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) and the circuit-switched modem connection.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] In this case, the maximum throughput is often called net bit rate or useful bit rate.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] To determine the actual data rate of a network or connection, the goodput measurement definition may be used.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] For example, in file transmission, the goodput corresponds to the file size (in bits) divided by the file transmission time.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] The goodput is the amount of useful information that is delivered per second to the application layer protocol.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Dropped packets or packet retransmissions, as well as protocol overhead, are excluded.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Because of that, the goodput is lower than the maximum throughput.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Often, a block in a data flow diagram has a single input and a single output, and operates on discrete packets of information.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Examples of such blocks are fast Fourier transform modules or binary multipliers.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Because the units of throughput (e.g., messages per second) are the reciprocal of the unit for propagation delay (e.g., seconds per message), throughput can be used to relate a computational block to a communications channel, simplifying system analysis.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] In wireless networks or cellular systems, the system spectral efficiency in bit/s/Hz/area, bit/s/Hz/site or bit/s/Hz/cell units, is the maximum aggregate throughput divided by the analog bandwidth and some measure of the system coverage area.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Throughput over analog channels is determined by the modulation scheme, the signal-to-noise ratio, and the available bandwidth.
[src:gcp-pubsub-lite/throughput] Since throughput is normally defined in terms of quantified digital data, the term *throughput* is not normally used; the term *bandwidth* is more often used instead.
